1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
Here's the entire pitch in one screen.

2
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:05,760
This is a $5 million raise on a $20 million pre.

3
00:00:05,760 --> 00:00:11,120
On a clean deal, founders take about $20.4 million at a $30 million exit.

4
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:13,440
Stack on three investor-friendly terms,

5
00:00:13,440 --> 00:00:17,280
and that drops to roughly $12.3 with control getting tighter, too.

6
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:19,760
That's term sheet tarot.

7
00:00:20,560 --> 00:00:24,480
It's a clause-reveal simulator for start-up financings.

8
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:30,880
You start with a standard venture deal, turn on specific terms,

9
00:00:30,880 --> 00:00:36,160
and instantly see what changes in ownership, payout, and board control.

10
00:00:38,080 --> 00:00:41,200
This clean Nova scenario is the baseline.

11
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,160
One time's non-participating preferred, no pool top-up, founder-led board.

12
00:00:49,120 --> 00:00:51,440
Nothing hidden, nothing dramatic.

13
00:00:54,480 --> 00:01:07,040
Now watch what happens when I add the double dip.

14
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:13,120
The investor takes preference off the top and still participates in the rest.

15
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:17,200
The payout bar reshuffles immediately,

16
00:01:17,200 --> 00:01:20,560
and the warning chips explain why this term matters.

17
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:23,280
Then I add the hidden pool.

18
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:27,920
Same round, same headline valuation,

19
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:31,840
but now the option pool gets topped up before pricing,

20
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:43,120
so dilution hits the existing holders first.

21
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:54,960
And this is where it gets more than financial.

22
00:01:55,920 --> 00:01:58,400
The crown seat changes governance.

23
00:01:59,360 --> 00:02:03,200
Board balance shifts, veto rights appear,

24
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:08,640
and the app makes that visible without making you read a wall of legal text.

25
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,360
The exit slider is one of my favorite parts.

26
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:20,720
Instead of a static term sheet,

27
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:25,680
you can scrub through outcomes and see exactly when the economics turn.

28
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:32,480
Low exit, medium exit, better exit, it all updates live.

29
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:47,120
Compare mode makes the product more practical.

30
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,960
On the left is a clause heavy nova deal.

31
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:54,960
On the right is a later stage pulse round.

32
00:02:55,840 --> 00:02:59,120
Same signals, very different consequences.

33
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:04,000
That's useful for coaching, negotiation prep,

34
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,480
or just building intuition fast.

35
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:32,000
You're not locked into canned examples either.

36
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:35,760
I can build a custom scenario,

37
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:38,400
launch it straight into the simulator,

38
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:42,080
and the same analysis stack comes along for the ride.

39
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:53,120
So this is a real model, not a fake walkthrough.

40
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:09,920
And once I've got a deal state I care about,

41
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:14,800
I can copy a link and reopen the exact scenario

42
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:17,760
with the same terms and exit assumptions.

43
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:28,960
That makes it easy to send a specific deal view to a co-founder, advisor, or investor.

44
00:04:29,120 --> 00:04:40,640
Under the hood, the app is transparent about the math.

45
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:45,760
The how it works page lays out the ownership calculation,

46
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:52,640
the pre-money pool top-up logic, the liquidation waterfall, and the control model.

47
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:02,240
That's the product.

48
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:06,880
Move one clause and the whole deal changes in front of you.

49
00:05:07,760 --> 00:05:14,480
For founders, that turns term sheet intuition from vague to visual in a couple of minutes.